2024 Outlook:
Baseball scouts, fantasy managers and fans alike had long foreseen future greatness in Acuna, and in 2023, his breakthrough arrived. The near-universal No. 1 prospect entering his 2018 debut season, one which culminated in his winning NL Rookie of the Year honors, Acuna added NL MVP honors to his growing résumé, becoming baseball's fifth-ever 40/40 (40 HR, 40 SB) and first 30/60 man, blowing past the latter threshold with his MLB-leading 73 stolen bases. Greater luck in the health department helped -- he played a personal-best 159 games after missing a combined 102 during three separate IL stints from 2020-22 -- but what made the biggest difference was a monstrous spike in his contact rate, which went from 71% in his first five seasons to 87%. Repeating the effort is a huge ask, as it's tough to follow up history with more history, but considering Acuna scored 133 more fantasy points than any player not named Shohei Ohtani while topping the Player Rater with its highest score by any player this century, regression would need to be steep to knock him from universal No. 1 overall selection status.

2024 Outlook:
Acquired by the Yankees via trade during the Winter Meetings, Soto will play his contract year in one of the most fantasy-friendly environments. Yankee Stadium's cozy confines inflated lefties' HR totals by 23% over the last three seasons and Soto is expected to bat second in a potent lineup, ahead of fellow slugger Aaron Judge. Considering Soto has often quietly delivered first-round fantasy value during the first six seasons of his big-league career -- his 2,535 fantasy points since his May 2018 debut are fifth-best in baseball and he already has three seasons of at least 500 points (2019, 2021 and 2023) -- the possibilities are tantalizing. He's a points-league building block thanks to his keen eye at the plate and top-shelf contact quality, and he has already been a top-25 Player Rater performer three times (2020, 2021 and 2023). If Soto can either sustain his .286/.399/.568, 20-HR second half, or shave a few percentage points off his 50% career ground-ball rate, he could top the points league leaderboard and perhaps even challenge for similar status in rotisserie formats.

2024 Outlook:
The Betts complaint department will engage only two claims -- his declining SB total as he has averaged just 12 over the last five seasons (after averaging 26 in the four before that) and the four games shy he was at shortstop from earning an unheard of (for a first-rounder) OF/2B/SS eligibility, although OF/2B is still an appealing and unusual combination in its own right. His profile is otherwise effectively spotless, coming off a year in which he hit a personal-best 39 home runs while delivering his second .300/.400/.500-plus season (his first reuslted in the 2018 AL MVP), one of only five qualified hitters to reach all three of those hitting-ratio thresholds. Most notably, Betts had the lowest qualified ground-ball rate, top-six fly ball and line drive rates, <i>and</i> a 94th-percentile average exit velocity, making him one of baseball's most well-rounded hitters. Oh, and he bats atop what is arguably baseball's most potent lineup. Betts is as strong a universal first-round option as they come.

2024 Outlook:
Few hitters have as well-rounded a skill set as Tucker, for whom "downside" appears to be entirely absent from his vocabulary. He's had three straight seasons of an 82%-plus contact rate (with categorical gains in each of those campaigns), 85th-percentile-or-better walk and chase rates in 2023, a near-identical career OPS against both right- (.855) and left-handed pitchers (.846), back-to-back 25/25 campaigns (which only he and Julio Rodriguez can claim) and an 86% SB success rate in those years. Tucker even finished 2023, his age-26 season, on a high note, batting .294/.385/.591 with 19 HR, 69 RBI, 16 SB and 61 runs scored over his final 80 games. That propelled him to top-10 finishes in both fantasy points and on our Player Rater, a feat which he has high odds of repeating in 2024.

2024 Outlook:
Ramirez remains a fantasy juggernaut despite a lackluster supporting cast. He totaled just 80 RBI last season, his fewest in a full season since 2016, but the third baseman ran wild after the break for his fifth career 20-20 season (and fifth in the last five full MLB seasons). His plate discipline is unwavering, as is his confidence. Ramirez's Barrel rate has sagged in recent years, but even so he ranked in the 96th percentile in xBA last season. Still just 31, Ramirez has put together the framework of a Hall of Fame career. Eventually the speed will dry up, but intent is most important when it comes to stolen bases, and Ramirez has shown over and over again that he likes to run. While there may be players on the board with more upside, few have Ramirez's track record of five-category excellence.

2024 Outlook:
One of the game's most feared sluggers, Alvarez has hit 30-plus homers, driven in 90-plus runs and had a hard-hit rate greater than 50% in each of the last three seasons -- the only player in baseball who can make that claim. Add his similarly elite form during the postseason as he's one of only 19 players in history with at least 100 total bases (115) and 40 RBI (41) in his playoff career -- while playing easily the fewest games (58) among that group -- and his is a first round-caliber skill set. Health has always been the one hindrance to Alvarez challenging for an MVP award or overall top-five fantasy status, as he has made three IL trips totaling 86 team games missed (excluding his four stints on the COVID-19 list) over his five-year career. If you're willing to take the dive, the prospective reward in the power departments could be massive.

2024 Outlook:
This machine keeps humming. Since the beginning of 2018, Freeman leads the majors in hits (1,030) and total bases (1,753), with substantial leads in both departments, and has matched Marcus Semien for the most games played (859), while also pacing all hitters with 2,821 fantasy points. Talk about a rules-change benefactor! Entering 2023, Freeman had never exceeded 13 steals in any season and had just a 71% success rate. Last season, he swiped 23 bags with a 96% success rate. This is as sound a skill set as they come, even as he enters his age-34 season. He's as locked-in a first-round talent -- across all styles of fantasy baseball play -- as they come.

2024 Outlook:
Devers exceeded 30 homers again in 2023, the third time he's done so in the last four full seasons. His .525 SLG over the last five years ranks 14th among qualified hitters in that span, and Devers' batting average has been above .270 in each of the last three years. Even with turnover and middling performance up and down the Boston lineup, Devers reached the century mark in RBI. Stolen bases are not a big part of Devers' game and his defensive metrics took a hit last year, though a move across the diamond is not expected to happen anytime soon. Devers will be 26 years old for the entirety of the 2024 season and projects as one of the AL's top run producers.

2024 Outlook:
Now <i>that's</i> the kind of season you'd expect from a 2019 first-rounder considered by many to be the top prospect in baseball at the time of his debut. Carroll became the first rookie in history to manage at least 25 HR and 50 SB, he finished third overall on our Player Rater and he helped propel his Diamondbacks to a World Series appearance. If there were any nits to pick, it would be that from July 1 forward, he had an average exit velocity 2.3 mph and a wOBA 43 points lower than before that date -- a concern only in that it coincided with his return from an injury to the same shoulder he had repaired in the minors in 2021. Carroll's winter rest, however, might serve as the cure for what ailed him, and he's a now-23-year-old with rotisserie superstardom in his future (perhaps even his <i>immediate</i> future). With a stellar spring training, he might be the kind of overall top-five pick he already is in rotisserie leagues.

2024 Outlook:
One of the most ballyhooed free agents in baseball history <i>despite</i> the elbow surgery that will prevent him from pitching until 2025, Ohtani's move to the powerhouse Dodgers lineup places him in about as fantasy-friendly a circumstance as there is for a hitter. The two-time AL MVP (2021, 2023) might well bat second between the NL's second- (Mookie Betts) and third-place (Freddie Freeman) finishers in the MVP race, and Dodger Stadium, despite its perception as being a pitching-friendly environment, was actually baseball's second-most HR-friendly venue over the last three seasons (a 22% boost relative to the average park). Now 29, Ohtani as a hitter alone is a more attractive (and foundational) rotisserie pick thanks to his combination of elite power and speed, than he is in points leagues. In the latter format, however, veteran players are well aware that "Ohtani the two-way player" is far and away -- a 'Wayne Gretzky circa the 1980s' type and the game's most-valuable asset. Tuck that away, keeper leaguers, as 2024 might well bring us his best year yet with the bat, while 2025 could bring us a 2021-23 redux.

2024 Outlook:
A lot went right for Olson during his career-year 2023, during which time he paced the majors in both home runs (54) and RBI (139). He extended his track record of stellar health -- he is the game's active "iron man," having played in 458 consecutive games -- and spent 83-of-162 games batting cleanup behind some three-man combination from Ronald Acuna Jr., Ozzie Albies, Michael Harris II and Austin Riley, all of them 3.0-plus WAR players with a .330-plus OBP. That's not to say that Olson's skill set wasn't worthy of his stat line. His swing is as power-oriented as they come, as he has a career 30% fly-ball rate and has had a 90th-percentile (or better) Statcast Barrel rate in five of the last six seasons. Plus, his .321/.430/.623 rates from Aug. 1 forward (during which time he had a much-improved 79% contact rate) signaled that Olson might well come close to repeating the effort. He's as sound a selection in the first two rounds as any hitter.

2024 Outlook:
Nobody will ever break Cal Ripken Jr.'s consecutive games-played streak, but Semien is the next best thing we have. He has exceeded 700 plate appearances in each of the last five full seasons and, should he do it again, he will become just the 19th player to ever have six such seasons. Semien's Wolverine-like health has been foundational for fantasy managers with him contributing positively in all five offensive categories, his best efforts coming in the run-scoring department. He has reduced his strikeout rate in each of the last four seasons and continues to be one of the tougher outs in the game. There is no reason to think we won't see more of the same from Semien this season as long as his body continues to hold up to the daily grind of the game. Enjoy the ride while it lasts.

2024 Outlook:
Witt's career is off to an outstanding start. The No. 2 overall pick in the 2019 amateur draft, he earned a No. 2 ranking in Kiley McDaniel's top 100 prospects list entering 2022, a year in which he broke camp and ultimately became just the fifth rookie in history with a 20/30 campaign (20-plus HR, 30-plus SB). Corbin Carroll became the sixth in 2023. Then, as a sophomore, Witt became only the fifth player in history at <i>any</i> career stage with at least as many as his 30 HR and 49 SB, earning himself the No. 4 overall spot on our Player Rater while scoring the 14th-most fantasy points (478). What might be his next step? Bear in mind that Witt, now 24, managed .311/.352/.576 rates, 18 homers and 26 steals over the Royals' final 81 games, meaning a universal first-round performance isn't an outrageous ask. He's as good a building block, particularly in keeper or dynasty leagues, as there is.

2024 Outlook:
Judge's follow-up to his AL record-setting 62 HR campaign wasn't far off the mark, at least through the Yankees' first 60 games of 2023, during which time he was on pace for 51 homers with a batting average just 20 points and slugging percentage 12 points off his 2022 final numbers. Unfortunately, a toe injury suffered in a collision with the RF wall at Dodger Stadium in said 60th game sent Judge to the IL for the eighth time in his big-league career, cost him the Yankees' next 42 games, and had an adverse impact upon his play thereafter. Most notably, his batting average dropped from .291 pre-injury to .249 afterwards. It was as demonstrative of Judge's fantasy outlook as any of his eight big-league years, between the massive statistical heights -- both in points-based <i>and</i> rotisserie scoring -- and the pitfalls present in his injury history.

2024 Outlook:
Fresh off three surgeries -- a pair on his left wrist and another for a torn labrum in his left shoulder, all three taking place between March and October 2022 -- and an 80-game suspension for failing a PED test in August 2022, Tatis failed to recapture his pre-injury form in his first season back in action. While a 25/25 (25-plus HR, 25-plus SB) season is nothing to scoff at, especially for a player sidelined for its first 20 games, Tatis ground-ball rate rose, his hard-hit rate declined, and he finished the year with a .224/.298/.371 line over San Diego's final 60 games-- a huge down note in which his contact rate was just 70%. Was this a new, post-surgery performance level for the now-25-year-old, or might it have been the lengthy recovery curve from shoulder ailments, for which the winter's rest might help? Spring training might provide hints of where his upside stands, but given his injury history, Tatis has a downside that makes him more of second-rounder rather than a first-round pick

2024 Outlook:
Guerrero has been surrounded by predictions of potential greatness for years, from his being the son of a Hall of Famer to his being regarded as the top international free agent at the time of his 2015 signing, to his status as baseball's No. 1 prospect entering his 2019 rookie season. And greatness he <i>did</i> achieve, during what was a near-MVP 2021 as a 22-year-old. However, in the two years since, he has failed to come close to replicating the effort. Beyond an inability to match his absurd .366 batting average and 26 homers against fastballs from that year, he had several minor bumps and bruises (wrist and knee, particularly) as well as struggles adapting to Rogers Centre's new OF dimensions. Guerrero probably has better numbers in his future, perhaps even immediately, and bear in mind he was pretty darned good in points leagues as is finishing tied for 39th overall in 2023 (411) and 31st in 2022 (443).

2024 Outlook:
Bregman appears to be poised for a big 2024 season in what could be his final season with Houston. The third baseman is one of just three players with more walks than strikeouts over the last two seasons, joining Luis Arraez and Juan Soto. That plate discipline makes him an ideal candidate to hit high in the lineup, and he did bat primarily from the second spot behind Jose Altuve last season. That could change under new manager Joe Espada, who could choose to move Kyle Tucker into the two-hole and slot Bregman in between Tucker and Yordan Alvarez (yes, please). Bregman gets his homers whether it be on the road or at home, and a contract year could see him approach the 30-HR plateau for the first time since 2018.

2024 Outlook:
After years of exhibiting beneath-the-radar outstanding skills metrics, Seager <i>finally</i> broke through with a season that might have been MVP-caliber if not for the presence of Shohei Ohtani. Seager set personal bests in batting average (.327), slugging percentage (.623), RBI (96), OPS+ (170), then continued his track record of October excellence that culminated in his Rangers capturing the World Series championship and earning himself World Series MVP honors for the second time. He became only the fourth player in history to win the award twice. And, despite all that, his tendency to miss time due to injury persisted, as he made two trips to the IL, one for a hamstring and one a wrist issue, marking the fifth time in the last six seasons that he had landed on the IL. Additionally, Seager had sports hernia surgery in late January, which could cost him much of spring training and perhaps even delay the start to his 2024 season. Seager's skills give him a first-rounder's upside, but beware the postseason buzz inflating his draft price or masking his checkered health history.

2024 Outlook:
After becoming the quickest player to reach 25 HR and 25 SB for a career as a rookie, Rodriguez in 2023 was the first player in history to deliver 25/25 numbers in both of his first two seasons. He also became the third-youngest member of the 30/30 club. J-Rod remains a superstar in the making, a future "top of the Player Rater" talent and league MVP candidate, but his current level of plate discipline makes him a tad overrated for points-league play. Invest at more of a second-round price in that format, barring signs of improvement during spring training.

2024 Outlook:
The No. 1 overall selection in the 2019 amateur draft and Kiley McDaniel's No. 1 prospect entering his 2022 rookie year, Rutschman is only beginning to write his story as the catching position's foremost superstar. Since his May 21, 2022, debut, he has scored a position-leading 684 fantasy points, driven by an elite level of plate discipline including 83% contact and 13.4% walk rates as a sophomore in 2023. He did that over 687 trips to the plate, the most by any player who appeared in at least half his games at catcher since Johnny Bench in 1974. That the Orioles regard his bat as critical enough to their lineup that they use the DH role to alleviate the defensive chores of catching helps. Rutschman even has room for growth, as his swing had more of a ground-ball lean last year than during his minor league days and his contact-quality metrics don't yet match the raves with which scouts have surrounded him for years. He's the catcher you want to build around in fantasy leagues. Perhaps not by a handy margin in 2024, but his lead probably isn't far off extending to "by leaps and bounds."

2024 Outlook:
After missing almost 100 games the previous season, Albies not only appeared in 148 contests in 2023, but he also delivered one of his most productive seasons to date. He missed some time in August due to a sore hamstring, but still set career-highs with 33 homers and 109 RBI. Albies even took advantage of the new rules by swiping 13 bases in 14 tries. Players often regress after achieving new personal bests, but Albies' exceptional contact skills should soften any fall. Mookie Betts may now be the No. 1 second baseman in fantasy baseball, but Albies remains a top option at the keystone.

The slugger feasted on fastballs, knocking 26 into the stands, but it's the non-fastballs which typically make or break Ozuna's numbers. In 2021, he hit fewer curves than Pedro Cerrano and, in 2022, the changeups gave him fits. Ozuna improved in both areas in 2023 which buoyed his batting average back to a more respectable number. Fantasy managers normally dislike filling the UT spot early in a draft, but Ozuna is arguably worth it as he is nestled in the middle of the most potent offense east of Los Angeles.

2024 Outlook:
Torres had his best season of strikeout rate, lowering his K% by eight full percentage points which helped elevate his batting average to its best level since the 2019 season. The return to a double-digit walk rate also gave him his best OBP of the last three seasons. Torres is the only primary second baseman other than Marcus Semien to have had at least 20 homers and 10 steals in both 2022 and 2023 -- but he will cost far less draft capital to acquire than Semien. Torres is heading into his final year before free agency and should be a lock for another 20-10 season with his ability to take aim at the short porch in right field in home games, where one-third of his homers landed.

2024 Outlook:
Ruiz was given the challenging task of taking over starting catching duties at the big-league level at the age of 22. He showed more confidence in his sophomore season, hitting 18 homers and driving in 67 runs. Ruiz, putting it kindly, is not at the position for his defensive abilities. He ranks among the worst catchers in the league in all defensive metrics while conversely ranking among the best at contact rate, strikeout rate and sweet-spot contact. The Nationals are not contending this season, so they can afford another season of development for Ruiz to see whether he can improve or if they need to move him to first base. The league runs wild on Ruiz, successfully converting 119 of their 140 SB attempts against him.

2024 Outlook:
Given a fresh start in Chicago on a one-year "prove-it" deal, Bellinger roared back with numbers reminiscent of his 2019 MVP campaign. Even a cursory glance under the hood, however, separated the stat lines. Bellinger's Statcast Barrel (6.1%) and hard-hit (31.4%) rates represented career worsts and his expected batting average (.268) was 52 points beneath his personal-best 2019 number. Nevertheless, he maintained elite statistics throughout, finishing with .313/.357/.552 rates, 17 HR and 68 RBI over 72 second-half games -- a signal that the shoulder woes that previously plagued him are now in the rearview mirror. So what is Bellinger for 2024? Where he winds up will have a say, but in all likelihood, he'll remain the high-contact, above-average-speed, decent-pop performer he just was, albeit it with some regression due. After finishing 11th overall on the Player Rater with the 28th-most fantasy points, we'll expect something closer to 50th and 75th for 2024.

2024 Outlook:
Nimmo remained healthy for consecutive seasons for the first time ever and set a career high in 2023 in both home runs and RBI. His skills have never really been in question, but injuries have repeatedly gotten in his way of success. Throughout all the setbacks, he remains extremely accepting of his walks which gives him an incredibly strong floor for those playing in OBP leagues, while his career shows just one poor batting average which came in one of the aforementioned injury-riddled seasons. The blemish on Nimmo's categorical production is that he just does not steal bases despite better-than-average sprint speed and a wealth of opportunities. We were surprised with the consecutive good health seasons, so where you draft Nimmo depends on how confident you are in the outfielder holding up in 2024.
